It is possible to measure the heart's electrical activity on the skin using an Arduino microcontroller. This is commonly known as an electrocardiogram (ECG) or electrocardiograph. 

To measure the heart's electrical activity, you will need to use an ECG sensor, such as the AD8232 ECG Sensor Module. This module can measure the electrical activity of the heart and output it in a format that can be read by an Arduino microcontroller. 

Here's a basic circuit diagram for connecting the AD8232 ECG Sensor Module to an Arduino:

```
AD8232 ECG Sensor Module   Arduino
-------------------------------
GND                        GND
3.3V                       3.3V
OUT                        A0
```

In this circuit, the GND pin of the ECG sensor is connected to the GND pin on the Arduino. The 3.3V pin of the ECG sensor is connected to the 3.3V pin on the Arduino to power the module. Finally, the OUT pin of the ECG sensor is connected to analog input pin A0 on the Arduino.

Here's a basic sketch that reads the analog input from the ECG sensor and prints the value to the serial monitor:

```
int ecgPin = A0;

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(9600);
}

void loop() {
  int ecgValue = analogRead(ecgPin);
  Serial.println(ecgValue);
  delay(10);
}
```

This sketch reads the analog input from the ECG sensor using the `analogRead()` function and prints the value to the serial monitor using the `Serial.println()` function. The `delay()` function is used to slow down the loop to prevent overwhelming the serial monitor.

Note that this is a very basic implementation of an ECG sensor, and there are many factors to consider when designing a reliable and accurate ECG system. It is important to ensure proper grounding and shielding to prevent interference and noise in the signal. It is also important to properly amplify and filter the signal to extract the relevant heart activity.
